what does hyper echoic mean hyperechoic is usually a term used to described the appearance of an area on an ultrasound hyperechoic means it returns more sound echoes to the probe hypoechoic would be less and isocechoic or homogenous would be same hyperechoic areas usually relate to fatty areas for example a hyperechoic liver is synonymis with a fatty liver or a hyperechoic nodule mass would be a lipoma fatty mass and almost always benign ultrasound can determine malignancy malignancy is associated with hypervascularity and usually hypoechoic masses hope that was helpful let me know if you need more info Medical ultrasonography Prostate cancer Hepatocellular carcinoma Ovarian cyst Cirrhosis Thyroid cancer Hepatitis Metastasis Malignant melanoma Cancer Uterine fibroids Renal cell carcinoma Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis Familial adenomatous polyposis Hypoglycemia Fatty acid Brain tumor Breast cancer Acute lymphoblastic leukemia Tuberous sclerosis Positron emission tomography Animal echolocation Ultrasound Vitamin Adenoma Atherosclerosis International Classification of Diseases for Oncology Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Colorectal cancer Stroke Gastrointestinal stromal tumor Insulin Cholesterol Benign prostatic hyperplasia Stomach cancer Esophageal cancer IgA nephropathy Glycogen storage disease type I Rhabdomyosarcoma Oncology Paracetamol Fat Ovarian cancer Radiology Benign intracranial hypertension Animism Loudspeaker Ascites Puberty Growth hormone Gynaecology Endometrial cancer Androgen insensitivity syndrome Cytogenetics Intravascular ultrasound Nutrition Hearing (sense) Alkaline phosphatase Omega-3 fatty acid Bowel obstruction Mammography Skin cancer Insulinoma Microbat Gravitational radiation Soap Thymoma Obstetrics Fatty acid metabolism Spiritual possession Sound Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia Hodgkin's lymphoma Gilbert's syndrome Tocotrienol Western blot Leukemia Medicine Caffeine Sensor Soft tissue sarcoma Vaginal bleeding Thyroid Varicocele D-dimer Endome